<br>
But.<br>
<br>
You can use the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Identify</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> spell to verify whether a person really does have a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> no drop</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> quest item. Learn how to use this spell and you can save yourself a lot of time and trouble.<br>
<br>
I've used <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Identify</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to verify that a person has quest items. I've also nailed a few people who just assumed that if it was <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> no drop</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and non-equippable they could just lie and say they had it when they didn't. Sorry bud, I'm not that naive.<br>
<br>
-----<br>
<br>
And what made me decide to start verifying <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> last piece</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> claims? An erstwhile friend of mine claimed last piece on a planar epic drop, and I deferred the piece to him so he could finish his epic.<br>
<br>
The next day, he spent eight consecutive hours in South Karana, and logged off after I had a ranger friend of mine step into the zone and see if anyone there was in search of a certain cloak from a certain flying horse.<br>
<br>
Turns out, his excuse was: &quot;Well, it was the last piece I needed other people to help me get.&quot; <br>
<br>
